Processing¶

In [41]:
def string_list_to_list_of_floats(string_list):
    '''
    Function transforms string containg list of numbers to list of floats or empty list
    Params: string_list[string] - string to convert
    Returns: [list] of [float]
    '''
    if pd.isnull(string_list):
        return []
    else:
        string_list = string_list.replace("[", "")
        string_list = string_list.replace("]", "")
        float_list = list(map(float, string_list.split(',')))
        return float_list
In [39]:
df = df.applymap(string_list_to_list_of_floats)
In [8]:
def get_plots_for_row(df, case):
    '''
    Function plot every cell of given case - every cell is a list of floats (or empty list).
    Params: df[pandas.DataFrame] - whole dataframe containg data to be ploted(and especially given case)
    case[string] - given case to plot only chosen row of data
    Returns: nothing
    '''
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(3, 3, figsize=(15,15))
    fig.suptitle(case)
    for i in range(len(df.columns)):
        metric = df.columns[i]
        data_for_plot = df.loc[case, metric]
        axs[i//3, i%3].plot(data_for_plot)
        axs[i//3, i%3].set_ylabel(metric)
In [9]:
def get_plots_for_each_case(df):
    '''
    Function to plot every case using get_plots_for_row().
    Params: df[pandas.DataFrame] - whole dataframe containg data to be ploted
    Returns: nothing
    '''
    for i in range(len(df.index)):
        case = df.index[i]
        get_plots_for_row(df, case)

In [43]:
def range_from_list(list_cell):
    return max(list_cell) - min(list_cell)
In [44]:
def mean_from_list(list_cell):
    return statistics.mean(list_cell)
In [45]:
def stdev_from_list(list_cell):
    return statistics.stdev(list_cell)
In [46]:
def max_over_min(list_cell):
    try:
        return max(list_cell)/min(list_cell)
    except(ZeroDivisionError):
        return 0
In [47]:
def is_increasing(list_cell):
    return pd.Series(list_cell).is_monotonic_increasing
In [48]:
def is_decreasing(list_cell):
    return pd.Series(list_cell).is_monotonic_decreasing
In [42]:
def get_metric_from_list(list_cell, metric_function):
    '''
    Function calculating some metric from list (if not empty).
    Params: listcell[list] of [floats] - list to be aggregated
    Returns: metric[float] - aggregation to be calculated // OR None if list is empty
    '''
    if len(list_cell) == 0:
        return None
    else:
        return metric_function(list_cell)
In [82]:
def get_df_modified_by_function(df, function):
    return df.applymap(lambda x: get_metric_from_list(x, function))

Normalization¶

Plots above doesn't provide much information due to disproportionate values of metrics. That's why i decided to normalize those metrics.

In [111]:
def get_normalized_df(df):
    return (df-df.min())/(df.max()-df.min())
In [112]:
normalized_df_stdev=get_normalized_df(df_stdev)
normalized_df_means=get_normalized_df(df_means)
normalized_df_ranges=get_normalized_df(df_ranges)
normalized_df_max_over_min=get_normalized_df(df_max_over_min)

Summary¶

In the given dataset there are 9 incidents and 8 normal cases presented.

There are no main metrics indicating incident, but it is possible to point the most extreme incident - incident_5. It stands out from rest of incindents looking at normalized plots. Of course success-rate is highly connected with incident detecting, but it's somehow self-explaining variable.

The analysis was focused and driven by variety of measured metrics.

Calculated metrics (standard deviation, mean, range, max/min) presented on plots#Plots of normalized statistics show that variety is bigger in incidents than in normal_cases.

It is mostly visible on #Variability of metrics where coefficients of variance of each metric are summed up for each case. Sum of cofficient of variance defines the type(incident/normal) with high certainty.
